description.value: Glazed composition two-sided solid plaque  ujat amulet of elaborate form, with three miniature ujat eyes above, surmounted by a couchant lion. Front is right eye, with raised ridges outlining eye, and 'tail' below which forms edge, and herringbone decoration on eyebrow above.  Three subsidiary eyes project in high relief and have curled round 'tails', but details abraded away.  Lion has narrow ruff marked with veritcal incisions. and longer incisions below for hair. Muzzle and ears rubbed off. At back large left eye rendered in same fashion, and subsidiary eyes, same as on front, but reversed, lion 's head and neck has long uneven striations for mane, while back of animal is smooth. Some piercings between subsidiary eyes.  Main perforation longitudinally  above main eye. Glaze surface has small areas of whitish coloured glaze remaining, core-creamy colour, very smooth and fine.

description.value: One small amulet and eight beads in different shapes and materials. A: One small amulet made of a glass-like material in a turquoise colour. The amulet itself has a thin and flat rectangular shape with a lug at the upper end. The area between the lug and the rest of the amulet is tapered and there are two notches at the lug end. The front of the body shows a diagonal groove and at the rear there are two horizontal grooves parallel to each other. Broken off at the lower end.  B: Two beads in a thin barrel-shape, one bead made of blue glass and with very shiny surface, the other made of white faience.  C: Two and a half cylindrical segmented beads, two very thin, one fragment of a wider bead. The best preserved example is 6 segments long, all made of blue faience. D: Two disc-shaped beads one made of blue faience, one made of ostrich eggshell, slightly irregular. E: One extended sphere bead made of blue faience.

description.value: Cylindrical pendant amulet: made from three cylindrical amethyst beads threaded on a copper alloy pin with a gold foil cap at the top and remains of a lower cap (now restored). The latter had lost its lid and is frayed around the edges. The upper cap is made from a conical piece of very thin sheet gold with a flat disc for a lid. A ring, scored with four lines, is soldered to the top. It has been worn away on both sides by the wire or thread on which it was suspended. The amethyst beads are separated by bands of gold foil which seem to be wrapped around the edges of the amethyst beads and not over a core. The middle bead has slipped out of the foil covering.

description.value: A cylindrical pendant amulet: made from a tube of sheet gold decorated with granulation in a chevron pattern of ten double rows, bordered at top and bottom by six triangles composed of granules. At either end is a conical cap formed from a flat disc attached to a hollow cone of sheet gold. The upper lid has a tube for suspension thread attached to it made from a piece of sheet gold rolled up and scored with nine lines cut with a chisel. The edges of the upper lid are slightly dented; the base of the lower cap is bent. The upper cap is removable. There are eight granules in the shaft's decoration to every 0.5 cm. The joins between individual granules and between granules and the sheet gold are visible. The gold around the granules is much lighter in colour than that on the plain ends of the tube. It may be that the granules were fixed together before being arranged on the tube. Most of them are joined to their own row and to the row beside them.

description.value: Glazed composition human-headed heart amulet: the pale blue inlaid heron on the purple blue upper surface is symbolic of the sun god and so has connotations of daily birth or renewal. The flat turquoise green underside bears in black the hieroglyphic text of Chapter 30B of the 'Book of the Dead', more often found on heart scarabs, which bound the heart to silence about its owner's misdeeds when it was weighed symbolically in the underworld. However, no owner is named. The separately inlaid red human face with striped wig can be considered to represent a personified heart.

description.value: A long string of fifty amulets amulets: of various materials, five beads and four pendants. The beads are all of glazed composition: the conical bead, mis-shapen barrel and oblate bead are all green, and two short barrels are blue. Three pendants are drop-shaped and made of cornelian, blue-green glazed composition and amethyst. The fourth is a flattened wide drop of amethyst.  Of the three baboon amulets two are of amethyst and one of cornelian. There are two green feldspar and three amethyst hawk amulets, two green jasper turtle amulets, one green feldspar 'ba'-amulet and two couchant lions,' one of steatite, the other of ivory. The string is completed by five hands, two fists, six hornets, four leg-with-foot amulets, three faces, four 'wedjat'-eyes, one shell-shaped amulet, one hippopotamus' head, one Taweret and one indeterminate amulet, all of cornelian.

description.value: Green jasper and gold heart-scarab of Sobekemsaf II: the human-headed jasper scarab is inset into a cloison in a hollow sheet gold plinth with a rounded back end. The rim of the cloison itself has been inset with an undulating strip of sheet gold to give the effect of granulation. description.value: Bronze menat-counterpoise amulet: this fine openwork amulet with details incised on both faces depicts the goddess Hathor in three separate manifestations. At the top she is in human form wearing a crown composed of upreared cobras. On one face the throne name of King Amenhotep III (Nebmaatre) is written in a cartouche just below her wig. On the other face the goddess's own epithet "Mistress of the sycamore fig" appears in the same place. The shaft of the counterpoise takes the form of Hathors fetish, which represents the handle of a sistrum or rattle. Here the goddess is characteristically frontally faced with cow's ears. The fetish stands on the hieroglyph for "gold," a reference to Hathor's epithet "the Golden One." In the roundel she takes the form of a cow, archetypal mother, wearing a sun disc between her horns (she was daughter of the sun god), and sailing through the marshes of the delta in a papyrus skiff.

description.value: Bead ornament with pendant discs: the beads are threaded on modern brass wire. The two principal types of bead are small orange-red hardstones described by Marshall as garnet, but looking more like cornelian, and spacer beads formed of a short spiral of fine gold wire. In addition, there are two small, blue-green faience beads and seven dark blue beads, probably of glass. Hanging from the string of beads are twenty-nine gold-and-pearl pendants. These consist of a pearl capped with gold at each end and a wire loop from which hangs a small gold disc with a cut-out (making a crescent shape) occupied by another small pearl on a wire. The disc element of one pendant is lost, and next to this defective pendant are two additional ornaments, an oval dark green glass bead and a small faience, uraeus pendant. The twisted gold wire which attaches the uraeus to the necklace looks modern.

description.value: A complete, brown, rectangular, leather amulet (higab), neatly stitched. The case was constructed by folding a leather strip across the bottom, sewing the two sides, folding the top over and sewing it closed. Space was left at the top fold for a string or cord to be inserted so that the amulet could be tied to the upper arm or around the neck. An apotropaic Arabic text written in black ink on paper was tightly folded several times to form a small square which was placed within the leather case. The text was wrapped in several layers of cotton fabric. The text consists of a magical rhombus of nine cells placed near the beginning of the inscription and 35 lines of Koranic and magical passages.

description.value: A cylindrical pendant amulet: made from a tube of sheet gold decorated with granulation in a chevron pattern of ten double rows, bordered at top and bottom by six triangles composed of granules. At either end is a conical cap formed from a flat disc attached to a hollow cone of sheet gold. The upper lid has a tube for suspension thread attached to it made from a piece of sheet gold rolled up and scored with nine lines cut with a chisel. The edges of the upper lid are slightly dented; the base of the lower cap is bent. The upper cap is removable. There are eight granules in the shaft's decoration to every 0.5 cm. The joins between individual granules and between granules and the sheet gold are visible. The gold around the granules is much lighter in colour than that on the plain ends of the tube. It may be that the granules were fixed together before being arranged on the tube. Most of them are joined to their own row and to the row beside them.
